{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01BCwXgzYuudbfq6a2wdwpFc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The goal is met. `output/calculation_note.md` exists and delivers everything required, derived offline from the inputs only.\n\n## Summary\n\nI built a pressure-vessel + Weibull + diffusion model (`output/triso_calc.py`) from the annex correlations alone, and wrote the note (`output/calculation_note.md`) with a supporting numeric record (`output/calc_output.txt`).\n\n**Central finding:** at ≤1800 °C the fission-gas pressure (17–29 MPa) produces only 70–124 MPa of SiC tangential stress after elastic load-sharing, while the IPyC/OPyC hold the SiC in −160 to −190 MPa residual compression (integrated from PyC swelling correlation (e) + the creep coefficient). Net SiC stress is **compressive in every case** — even the worst Monte-Carlo geometric tail reaches only +70 MPa vs an 873 MPa strength. So the over-pressure mechanism fails ≈0 particles, robustly (survives +30% CO and 50% loss of compression).\n\n**Per case (failed particles / onset / Kr-85 / Cs-137):**\n- **A1** — 1600 °C/500 h: 0 failures; Kr ≲6×10⁻⁵ (below detection); Cs ≈0.11\n- **A2** — 1800 °C/100 h: 0–2 (degradation tail, during 1800 °C phase); Kr ~6×10⁻⁵–1×10⁻⁴; Cs ≈0.07\n- **B** — 1800 °C staged/400 h: 0–5 (mostly final 300 h phase); Kr ~6×10⁻⁵–3×10⁻⁴; Cs ≈0.13 — **worst**\n- **C1** — 1600 °C/304 h, 13.9%: 0 failures; Kr ≲6×10⁻⁴; Cs ≈0.083 (highest activity of pair)\n- **C2** — 1600 °C/304 h, 11.1%: 0 failures; Kr ≲6×10⁻⁴; Cs ≈0.083 — least severe\n\n**Ranking:** B > A1 ≳ A2 > C1 > C2. Temperature dominates (Arrhenius), time multiplies it (B's 400 h at 1800 °C makes it worst), and burnup sets inventory/pressure not the release fraction — cleanly shown by the C1/C2 pair (same Cs fraction, C1 higher activity and pressure).\n\n**Most uncertain assumption:** the Cs-137 effective diffusion length through intact SiC — it swings the absolute Cs fraction over an order of magnitude (7–95%). The ranking and the Kr/failure conclusions are high-confidence; the absolute Cs magnitudes are low-medium.\n\nEach number carries an explicit assumption and confidence level in §6. I flagged the internal factor-~5.6 inconsistency in the printed Eq 10.9 coefficients and used the annex's stated 1600 °C anchor as instructed."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":131,"cache_creation_input_tokens":714,"cache_read_input_tokens":81488,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":714},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4b3d406f-4e66-44c2-8ed1-d166103fe542","uuid":"1f594cbe-782a-4a85-a2fd-0d540087c60a","request_id":"req_011Cce1Bzj3K7hC822LCbJiR"}
